    <text>
        <body>
            <div frus:doc-dateTime-max="1920-06-07T23:59:59-05:00"
                frus:doc-dateTime-min="1920-06-07T00:00:00-05:00" n="210"
                subtype="historical-document" type="document" xml:id="d210">
                <note rend="inline" type="source">701.1211/255a</note>
                <head>
                    <hi rend="italic">The Chief of the Division of Mexican Affairs, Department of
                        State</hi> (<persName type="from">
                        <hi rend="italic">Johnston</hi>
                    </persName>) <hi rend="italic">to the Second Assistant Secretary of State</hi>
                        (<persName type="to">
                        <hi rend="italic">Adee</hi>
                    </persName>)</head>
                <opener>
                    <dateline rendition="#right">[<placeName>
                            <hi rend="smallcaps">Washington</hi>
                        </placeName>,] <date calendar="gregorian" when="1920-06-07">
                            <hi rend="italic">June 7, 1920</hi>
                        </date>.</dateline>
                </opener>
                <p>
                    <hi rend="smallcaps">Dear Mr. Adee</hi>: The Mexican Chargé d’Affaires, being
                    apprehensive that his political adversaries might attempt a forcible entrance of
                    the Embassy, asked that a special patrolman be stationed there continuously.</p>
                <p>To this oral request, repeated by this Division, the Chief of Police responded
                    with alacrity.<note n="26" xml:id="d210fn26">Police detail was assigned to the
                        Mexican Embassy May 13, and withdrawn June 5.</note>
                </p>
                <closer>
                    <signed>C. M. J[<hi rend="smallcaps">ohnston</hi>]</signed>
                </closer>
            </div>
        </body>
